<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Lord Donoughue accused on Maxwell stock lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE directors of Mirror Group Newspapers, who were also pension fund
trustees until December 1991, told a Parliamentary Select Committee
yesterday they did not know assets were disappearing from the pension fund.
Mr David Shaw MP asked the trustees if they had been told why Lord Donoughue
resigned in July 1991 from the board of Bishopsgate Investment Management,
the Maxwell-controlled company which managed most of the MGN scheme's
investments. In December 1991, Lord Donoughue said publicly he resigned
after Mr Maxwell refused to tell the trustees about BIM's stock lending. He
said he believed it had been proper but was concerned it was occurring
without his knowledge.
'Would you say that following vigorous exchanges, Robert Maxwell and Lord
Donoughue appear to have come to an understanding that Lord Donoughue should
leave the company in the full knowledge that something was wrong without
blowing the whistle?' Mr Shaw asked Mr Ernest Burrington, a trustee of MGN's
pension fund until Mr Maxwell's death. 'The answer must be yes,' Mr
Burrington replied.
In a letter from his solicitor in December 1991, Lord Donoughue said he
became aware that BIM was lending stock without his knowledge and asked it
to cease. By July, he asked Mr Maxwell to notify all pension fund trustees
of its occurrence. He resigned two weeks later.
