<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Lonrho may seek early end to VAG deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONRHO, the international trading conglomerate, may negotiate an early end
to its Volkswagen/Audi import and distribution operations in the UK which
account for more than one-fifth of its worldwide turnover.
The news follows a report last month that the German car-maker had planned
to take control of the business when the existing contract expires at the
end of 1993.
But Lonrho, which is understood to be pessimistic about the future of all
non-Japanese car sales in the UK, believes it may be in its interest to
negotiate an early end to the arrangement.
Seven years ago, the pre-tax profit forecasts for 1990 for the business
operated by VAG, a Lonrho subsidiary, were around Pounds 60m.
However, last year taxable profits fell by 11 per cent to Pounds 20m from
Pounds 22.6m a year earlier.
The alternative now being considered is to negotiate an early end to the
contract this year which could be worth Pounds 160m: assets are valued at
Pounds 100m and compensation for an early cessation of the contract could be
worth another Pounds 60m.
If this happened, Lonrho would be likely to take the extra Pounds 60m above
the line, boosting this year's overall pre-tax profits.
While the extra UK profits would help mitigate this year's problems over
advance corporation tax (ACT), in the long term the loss of the UK business
would be likely to add to them.
Its 1990 accounts show that there was Pounds 79m of unused ACT because the
group does not make sufficient profits to offset fully against ACT.
VAG's pre-tax profits accounted for almost 10 per cent of Lonrho's total
pre-tax profits of Pounds 207m in the year to September 1990.
Mr Charles Pick, conglomerate analyst at Nomura, said: 'The group are
indicating that change may not necessarily be a bad thing if it comes,
especially if VAG's future profits are impaired by the rising market share
of Japanese transplant product in the UK new car market.'
VW, the leading European car-maker, is keen to control distribution in all
five European large volume markets. In recent years it has added ownership
of the Spanish and Italian operations to its control in Germany and France.
However, Lonrho remains adamant that it has not been told that Volkswagen
wants to take control of the business operated by VAG and it may still renew
the contract in 1993.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
