<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Humber coal port project scrapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS FOR Britain's largest coal import terminal have been abandoned after a
row between Associated British Ports and PowerGen, one of two electricity
generators involved in the Pounds 150m project.
It was to have been built at Immingham on the Humber. Contracts for its
construction were close to being awarded.
Scheduled to open in 1994, the terminal would have posed a serious threat to
British Coal by allowing generators to replace 10m tonnes a year of the 65m
tonnes of coal now purchased from it annually.
ABP, manager of the project, yesterday blamed cancellation on the refusal of
one generator - understood to be PowerGen - to agree to sign final contracts
this week. The other generator involved in the project is National Power.
Sir Keith Stuart, ABP's chairman, said: 'We finally decided that enough was
enough.'
ABP has had parliamentary permission to develop the site since June 1990 and
still wants to go ahead with the project for other dry goods. 'We have lost
valuable time,' Sir Keith said.
It was claimed yesterday that PowerGen had asked ABP to delay the final
signing of the project until after the general election.
'The Labour party had a go at them and said they would let the terminal rot
if they got in,' a senior coal industry executive said.
'PowerGen is not a big partner in the project, and they were prepared to
hold off till after the election, but ABP forced the pace,' he said.
Mr Frank Dobson, the shadow energy secretary, said the Labour party had made
it clear that the coal terminal would have been 'a white elephant' under a
Labour government.
PowerGen acknowledged it had not welcomed the political attention focused on
the project, especially after it was disclosed last week that the contracts
were about to be signed.
The company stressed, however, that it had not agreed when the final
signature would take place.
'Our negotiations on this deal were ongoing and we believe the action ABP
has taken is precipitous,' the company said.
PowerGen denied it lacked commitment to the terminal project, which it had
itself initiated. National Power said ABP's decision was 'not in accordance
with the company's wishes'.
Both generators will now look at alternative import terminal projects.
ABP will now seek other ways of developing the Immingham site. Because of
lack of capacity at Immingham, many of ABP's existing customers would be
interested in new facilities, ABP said.
Irish Sea gas field project approved, Page 6
</TEXT>
