<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Names reassured on Lloyd's probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DISPUTE over the appointment of Sir David Walker to head an inquiry into
alleged malpractices at the Lloyd's insurance market was defused yesterday
at a meeting between Conservative MPs, leading Names and the market
authorities.
Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, chairman of an action group of Names - individuals
whose wealth backs underwriting - said he was now convinced of the
independence of Sir David, chairman of the Securities and Investment Board,
who also attended yesterday's meeting.
Sir David's appointment on Friday followed allegations in parliament that
Names working in the market were benefiting at the expense of outside Names.
The Lloyd's Council admitted yesterday that 'some syndicates with a greater
than average participation of external Names are syndicates that have
incurred very substantial losses from catastrophe business'.
This was 'based on a snap-shot at a point in time' and did not 'necessarily
indicate that these syndicate compositions result from improper practice in
the allocation of syndicate capacity'. It was necessary to examine 'how the
composition has developed over time'.
The admission came in a dossier, provided to Names and MPs, drawn up in
response to questions raised by Mr Paul Marland, a Conservative MP who is
also a Lloyd's Name.
Earlier in the week some Names had questioned the appointment of Sir David,
who is also a member of the Lloyd's Council, the market's governing body.
Mr Doll-Steinberg, representing Names on catastrophe reinsurance syndicates
formerly managed by Gooda Walker agency, said he was impressed with Sir
David's forthrightness.
'We had some reservations at the beginning, but having heard him and met
him, whatever reservations we had have been unconditionally withdrawn.'
Together with a delegation of four Conservative MPs, including Sir William
Clark, chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee, and three other
Names' leaders, Mr Doll-Steinberg met Sir David and leaders of the Lloyd's
market, including Mr David Coleridge, chairman, and Mr Alan Lord, chief
executive, yesterday.
Names on Gooda Walker, which managed a number of syndicates that have
suffered devastating losses in 1989 and 1990, are among those seeking
injunctions to prevent Lloyd's drawing down from the Names' funds to meet
cash calls.
Sir William said he had received 'categorical assurances' that Sir David's
terms of reference would be 'as wide as anything'.
Sir David would be able to investigate any allegation, he said.
Observer, Page 16
</TEXT>
