<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM defends a 'prudent' rise in PSBR
 -Economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday further heightened expectations of substantial tax
cuts in the March 10 Budget by saying Britain was in a better position than
ever before to 'borrow prudently'.
The prime minister's forceful justification of an increased Public Sector
Borrowing Requirement (PSBR) followed Labour accusations that he was
back-tracking on comments last year that extra borrowing would lead to
higher taxes.
However, Downing Street said there was no conflict, arguing that the PSBR
depends on other factors besides tax levels. Mr Major quoted comments he
made when chief secretary to the Treasury in 1987 that it would be right in
a recession to increase borrowing.
A senior Downing Street official said the disciplines of European exchange
rate mechanism membership justified the use of fiscal policy to offset the
deflationary impact of using interest rates to control sterling.
Expectations of substantial tax cuts as the centrepiece of a Tory manifesto
for an April 9 election are now widespread.
Mr Major told the Commons: 'we are now in a better position to borrow
prudently than we have been at any stage in the past - to borrow prudently
and maintain our commitment to a balanced budget in the medium term'.
Mr Major gave his ritual assurance that he could not anticipate the
proposals to be introduced by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor.
This was brushed aside by Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, who predicted
that the additional money borrowed would be used to finance election
'bribes'.
To Labour cheers, he called on the prime minister to explain which taxes
would go up to pay for the 'bribes'.
Mr Kinnock cited a Conservative pamphlet, Transforming Britain, published
last year. In it Mr Major wrote: 'If borrowing takes the strain, taxes - not
just our taxes, but the next generation's too - have to go up to service the
debt. And inflation rises with equally calamitous results.'
Last night, however, Conservative Central Office defended Mr Major's
comments, saying they in fact highlighted 'the point we wish to drive home
about Labour' over the need for sensible tax and spending policies.
Two former Conservative chancellors, Sir Geoffrey Howe and Mr Nigel Lawson,
listened from opposite ends of the Commons chamber as Mr Major recalled how
between them they had reduced the PSBR.
Later, however, Mr Major said that Mr Lawson's decision to cut interest
rates following the 1987 stock exchange crash had been a mistake.
Mr Major also reminded Mr Kinnock that the PSBR of the last Labour
government amounted to 9 1/2 per cent of gross domestic product - Pounds
55bn at current prices.
Mr Chris Smith (Lab Islington South and Finsbury) equated borrowing to buy
votes at a general election to 'fiscal philandering of the worst kind'. The
prime minister countered that the last Labour government had cut taxes in
advance of the 1979 election 'on the back of a huge borrowing requirement'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
