<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: A hidden hand for the opposition -
The role of Labour's backroom planner, Jim Parish
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THEY SHUN the limelight. But even the most glittering frontbench stars would
be lost without them.
Backroom tacticians will play a critical role in communicating the general
election messages of their respective parties. None craves greater anonymity
or has a more important role to play than Labour's Mr Jim Parish.
As the party's chief campaigns officer he will act as all-purpose stage
manager-cum-technician for the scores of set-piece media events before
polling day.
Drawing on one of his favourite slim panatellas he will oversee the design
and erection of the sets, the installation of sound systems and lighting and
the entrances and exits of the dramatis personae.
These skilfully crafted backdrops exert a subtle but profound influence on
how Labour's front-line performers are perceived, particularly by television
viewers.
The political impact of a slogan which catches the popular mood, or
conversely of an unflattering set or technical glitch, could set the tone
for the entire campaign.
A gaunt figure, with a mop of greyish hair and a resemblance to actor James
Coburn, Mr Parish likens his role to that of Lilian Baylis, the stage
manager who 'used to fry eggs and bacon' in the wings of the Old Vic
theatre.
This portrait is supplemented by the comments of two reverential colleagues.
Mr Philip Gould, the party's advertising specialist, says: 'Jim is central
to the improvement in Labour's presentation.
Mr Peter Mandelson, Labour's former communications director now standing for
parliament, says: 'I used to call him my impresario. Jim was one of those
who brought about the transformation of the party's image for which I was
subsequently given much of the credit.'
Colleagues say he can sometimes be 'prickly' in his determination to get
things right. But he is a popular figure with journalists, who appreciate
his convivial manner and knack of telling original jokes.
After an early career encompassing the BBC, West End theatre and British
Olivetti, he joined Labour as a press officer between the two general
elections of 1974. Then, he recalls, the party's notion of publicity was
'for the head of communications to call a meeting and say: 'We have got a
conference coming up in two weeks and we need a slogan - anyone got any
ideas?'.'
It is easy to forget it was only in 1983 that Labour lavished Pounds 7,500
on its very first conference set.
He identifies a number of significant presentational milestones since then.
First, the 1984 campaign for elections to the European Parliament, which was
the first to employ 'publicity techniques that are now taken for granted'.
Then the conception and design of the now ubiquitous Labour rose.
He also highlights the launch of the 1987 general election manifesto at a
plush conference centre. 'The Tories launched their manifesto in Central
Office on the same day. They looked cramped. We looked stylish. We didn't
look back after that.'
Today, Labour's sets are imbued with a classy, uncluttered quality -
off-white decor, off-centre lectern and copious rose-bowls - which is Mr
Parish's hallmark. His chief aim in this is to focus attention on the
speaker and help to 'clarify' the message.
He expects this general election to be the first fully to exploit satellite
communications, with the result that parties will engage in 'hour-to-hour
combat'.
It will also be a race for the early bird, with Labour's morning press
conferences starting at 7.45am sharp.
'It is about trying to grab the issue of the day,' he explains, dismissing
as 'boy scoutish' the Liberal Democrat move to summon the press at 7.15am.
</TEXT>
