<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour takes three-pointpoll lead -
Public Opinion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR has taken a three-point lead over the Tories in the latest opinion
poll, which shows them with 41 per cent to 38 per cent for the government.
The ICM survey, in today's Daily Mail, also indicates that almost half of
those questioned - including just over a quarter of Labour voters - believe
that the recession would end more quickly if the Budget contains tax cuts.
Labour is due to continue its attack on the government's taxation and
borrowing plans at a press conference today.
More worryingly for the Tories, Mr John Major's popularity fell six points
to 36 per cent, while the rating for Mr Neil Kinnock as a potential prime
minister has risen by three points to 24 per cent.
The Tories have slipped three points since last month's ICM poll, which
showed them on 41 per cent - a one point lead over Labour. It is their
lowest ICM rating since July.
The Liberal Democrats' showing has risen to 17 per cent from 13 in January.
The 48 per cent of those saying they believe economic recovery will come
more quickly with tax cuts compares with about one-third who believe
recovery will begin more quickly through government expenditure.
Tax cuts as a way to help the economy are favoured by seven out of ten Tory
voters, 27 per cent of Labour voters and 41 per cent of Liberal Democrats.
Labour is confident that the lead represents a breaking of the deadlock in
the polls, but the Tories can argue that it is still within the three per
cent margin for error.
ICM interviewed 1,557 people in 54 constituencies last Friday and Saturday.
</TEXT>
