<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Jet partnership with Japanese discussed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace is discussing with Japan's three leading aerospace
companies a possible partnership in its 146 regional jet programme. The
three are Kawasaki Heavy Industries, Fuji Heavy Industries and Mitsubishi
Heavy Industries.
BAe has been seeking industrial partners for its regional jet programme,
which has suffered from the downturn in civil aviation and the acute
financial difficulties of smaller airlines.
BAe executives confirmed yesterday that the company had talked with several
European and Japanese manufacturers but that it was particularly interested
in an alliance with Japan.
A Japanese partnership would boost BAe's presence in the Asia-Pacific civil
aircraft market, which is expected to grow strongly in the next 10 years.
The Japanese companies are interested in a partnership venture with an
established western aerospace manufacturer which would give them access to
the development of a commercial aircraft programme rather than just
sub-contracting work.
Mitsubishi has discussed co-operation in the regional aircraft sector with
Deutsche Aerospace. These talks are understood not to have progressed.
BAe has offered the Japanese manufacturers an opportunity to join its 146
programme, including development of a 100-seat regional airliner.
The European Airbus consortium, in which BAe has a 20 per cent stake, has
also held preliminary talks with the big three Japanese companies. This was
to discuss a possible partnership in the development of a very large Airbus
aircraft programme, involving a 600-seater jumbo airliner towards the end of
the decade.
The Japanese companies have so far been tied to the US Boeing company, the
world's largest manufacturer of commercial aircraft, but their role in
Boeing programmes has involved only sub-contracting work.
BAe and Airbus would offer the Japanese an opportunity to share in the
development of commercial aircraft programmes, something Boeing has been
reluctant to do.
BAe has been seeking a partnership to rationalise its loss-making 146
business as part of its overall restructuring strategy. The UK group has
called for a rationalisation of the regional aircraft industry, where
competition has become intense because of the large number of rival aircraft
programmes.
BAe's link with the Japanese Honda car group in its Rover car subsidiary has
helped increase the UK company's visibility in the Japanese market.
The Japanese companies have also shown interest in BAe's profitable jet
business involving the 125 corporate aircraft family. BAe has made it clear,
however, that it is not considering selling this concern at this stage.
</TEXT>
