<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: White paper on health set for delay
 -News in Brief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLICATION of the planned white paper on preventive health care is to be
delayed until after the election, in an embarrassing setback for the
government, Alison Smith writes.
The emphasis on preventive care was intended to form part of the Tories'
counter-attack to Labour's onslaught over the national health service.
The Treasury, however, is said to have argued that the implications of the
proposals meant that they could not be launched before the Budget.
Ministers were then advised that there would not then be enough time to
publish them as government policy before running into the election campaign,
if - as expected - it begins in mid-March.
The green paper on a 10-year plan to make the UK healthier was published
last June and the consultation period finished at the end of October.
*****
EDUCATION: Labour will abolish England's remaining grammar schools and end
all selection at 11 if it wins the election, Mr Jack Straw, shadow education
secretary, said yesterday.
Mr Straw said grammar and secondary modern schools would be integrated into
'full fledged comprehensive schools.'
He attacked the government's readiness to increase the number of grammar
schools by allowing schools which have opted out of local authority control
to change their status.
*****
CANDIDATES: Labour yesterday selected candidates to fight Liverpool Broad
Green and Coventry South East at the general election in place of MPs Mr
Terry Fields and Mr Dave Nellist, expelled in December for alleged links
with Militant.
Ms Jane Kennedy, a 33-year-old union official, will defend the Liverpool
seat where Mr Fields had a 6,047 majority in 1987. Mr Jim Cunningham will
defend Mr Nellist's 6,653 majority. The expelled MPs have said they will
contest the seats.
</TEXT>
