<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Baker initiative on bail offences
attacked - Law and Order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT measures aimed at cracking down on 'bail bandits' who re-offend
before coming to trial met charges of blatant electioneering from opposition
parties yesterday.
Mr Kenneth Baker, home secretary, argued that a considerable toughening of
the law was necessary to deal with 'the hard core who persistently
re-offend'. Last year some 50,000 out of half a million people granted bail
were convicted of offences while on remand, up from 35,000 five years ago,
he said.
He went on to outline legislation to make offending when on bail a factor to
be taken into account by courts when sentencing, improved means for
identifying likely re-offenders and an Pounds 8m grant to increase the
number of bail hostels.
The timing of the initiative met with scorn from Labour and the Liberal
Democrats. While formally welcoming several of the measures, they said that
a doubling of the crime rate to more than 5m cases a year since 1979 had
demolished the Conservatives' case to be the natural party of law and order.
Mr Baker's Commons statement of the crackdown on bail offenders was widely
seen in Westminster as a bid to upstage Labour's attempt to take the
initiative as the Liberal Democrats also levelled charges of government
complacency.
The rising tide of crime now frequently ranks in the top five issues of
greatest concern to voters, according to opinion polls. Politicians are also
aware that definitive crime figures are due to be published towards the end
of March, when an election campaign is thought almost certain to be under
way.
Leaks have suggested that these could show a 20 per cent rise in crime in
the past year alone - a potentially highly damaging blow to the Tories.
Labour officials said yesterday that private polling has shown they now lead
the Tories by 40 points to 34 when voters are asked which party would be
good or excellent at tackling crime.
Yesterday Mr Hattersley said a Labour government would meet demands from
chief constables for an increase of up to 3,000 in police strength.
Economies within the Home Office, including reducing numbers of remand
prisoners held in police stations, could finance the increase, he claimed.
</TEXT>
