<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Blunkett warns of 'shambles' -
Local Government Reorganisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'PIECEMEAL' approach proposed by ministers for re-organising local
government would lead to shambles and a period of blight, Mr David Blunkett,
the opposition local government spokesman, warned yesterday.
Speaking during the final Commons stages of the legislation that sets up a
commission to review local government, Mr Blunkett said an incoming Labour
government would ensure that the review covered the country as a whole
comprehensively, and produced plans - ideally within two years - followed by
a period of consultation.
In this way, he said, people 'would be able to see the pattern of local
government emerging across the country'.
There would then be a single vesting day to avoid a time when staff left
councils which were to be abolished and services began to disintegrate, but
new authorities were not yet in place.
The government's ideologically driven approach, he said, meant that it had
missed the opportunity of consensus and lasting change.
Mr Michael Portillo, the local government minister, accused Labour of
manufacturing disagreement with the government, and described the bill as
'unusually enlightened'.
He condemned Labour's commitment to a system of unitary authorities rather
than allowing some two-tier local government, describing it as 'devised in
Whitehall, imposed on local people, all at one go in one big bang,
standardised and socialist'.
Responding to pressure from Tory backbenchers, Mr Portillo said the
government would look again at the guidance to the commission.
This should ensure that it reflected the differences between people's
expectations of the localities which should meet their needs and the areas
through which services could be provided efficiently.
</TEXT>
