<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Apex Trust terms are accepted by
creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of Apex Trust, the charity that provides training for
ex-offenders, seemed more assured yesterday after creditors, including the
Department of Employment, accepted terms from court-appointed
administrators.
Apex Trust has been fighting voluntary liquidation since January because of
cashflow shortfalls - after the setting up of Training and Enterprise
Councils (Tecs), which pay training providers in arrears - and muddles over
government payments.
The latter included a demand by the Department of Employment in January for
repayment of Pounds 250,000 which it said it had paid to Apex last year.
The department yesterday effectively wrote off the Pounds 250,000 when it
and other unsecured creditors agreed to terms put to them by Cork Gully, the
joint administrator. Unsecured creditors were owed Pounds 1.5m.
Preferential creditors, including the Inland Revenue and Apex employees,
agreed to accept payments due to them, amounting to about Pounds 300,000, in
four equal instalments starting in April.
The administration period will now extend to the end of March while the
administrators continue to negotiate the necessary funding from the Home
Office and the private sector. Cork Gully declined to say how much was
needed.
The charity had an overdraft of about Pounds 50,000 at the time of the
government demand.
Cork Gully said there was a 'reasonable chance' of Apex surviving. It did
not have money in hand to cover preferential creditors but had a number of
firm pledges of money.
</TEXT>
