<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Union threat over leaked Ford
relocation proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION leaders at Ford UK yesterday promised 'a major reaction' if the
company goes ahead with a plan to slim down two research and development
centres at Dunton and Aveley in Essex and concentrate R&amp;D work in Germany.
A document leaked to the AEU engineering union talks of shrinking Dunton,
Ford's biggest R&amp;D centre in Europe, and Aveley, as an 'option' which 'does
not represent company policy'.
If the plan did go ahead it would mean transferring to Germany about 1,200
of the 4,000 jobs at the two centres. The AEU believes that it could quickly
lead to the closure of all R&amp;D facilities in the UK and the loss of 12,000
jobs.
Union officials are convinced that even if the company shelves the option
under discussion it will want to shift more R&amp;D work to Germany.
Mr Jimmy Airlie, the AEU's senior Ford official, said: 'Dunton and Aveley
provide core services for Ford. If they are removed, the writing is on the
wall for Ford as a major manufacturer in Britain.'
Ford said the document was part of 'an ongoing study into engineering
activities in Europe'.
The company denied any immediate plans for a major job transfer to Germany,
but pointed out that other big car manufacturers have only one important R&amp;D
centre in Europe.
Merkenich, near Cologne, where most of the Dunton jobs would go, is almost
the same size as Dunton.
Mr Lindsey Halstead, Ford of Europe chairman, recently denied that Dunton
would be closed, pointing out that the company had just invested Pounds 156m
there.
