FT  26 FEB 92 / M6 to be widened after plan for private toll rival scrapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has abandoned plans for a privately financed toll motorway
between Manchester and Birmingham. Instead it proposes to widen the existing
M6 motorway from three lanes to four in each direction.
The Transport Department said last night that the decision was taken 'for a
variety of reasons, ranging from environmental to operational'.
The turnaround was criticised by Mr John Prescott, shadow transport
secretary, who said the government's ideological commitment to privately
financed roadbuilding had caused delays to essential road schemes.
Mr Prescott said companies which had been asked to submit preliminary bids
for the motorway 'must now be sceptical about other private road-building
plans'.
The British Road Federation said the revised proposals would not solve the
need for extra motorway capacity between Manchester and Birmingham. If a
private road was not to be built, a public-sector motorway should be
provided in its place. The federation said that, at the very least, the M6
should be widened to five lanes in each direction.
The Transport Department estimated that the extra lanes for the M6 between
junctions 11 and 20 would cost Pounds 450m. The department hoped that the
work will start in 1996 and last two to four years. The road would be
widened by building another two lanes on one side of the existing motorway.
The private road plan attracted four bids last year. Members of the groups
included Balfour Beatty, Tarmac and Trafalgar House from the UK; Italstat,
the Italian toll road operator; Cofiroute, the French toll road operator;
and French contractors GTM International and SOGEA.
The Transport Department yesterday announced that it would seek bids to
build a privately financed motorway to the west of Birmingham. The road
would link with the northern relief road, which is also to be privately
financed, and create an orbital, mostly tolled, road around the city.
</TEXT>
