<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Murray Johnstone slashes entry charge for unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILLIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MURRAY JOHNSTONE, the Glasgow-based fund management group, is cutting the
initial charge on its unit trusts from about 5 per cent to 1 per cent in a
move which could spark competition in the retail investment industry,
Phillip Coggan writes.
The unitholder pays the initial charge as part of a spread between the offer
price (at which the investor buys) and the bid price (at which the investor
sells). The greater the spread, the more the fund will have to rise in value
before the investor makes a profit.
By cutting the initial charge the spreads on Murray Johnstone's funds will
average about 2.6 per cent, compared with an average of about 6 per cent for
the sector. In other words, investors backing these funds will have a 'head
start' of more than 3 per cent.
Murray Johnstone is raising its annual charge from 1 per cent to 1.5 per
cent. But this higher level is not unusual.
In the US many mutual funds (the equivalent of unit trusts) have small or
non-existent initial charges. These 'no-load funds' have cornered a big
share of the market.
The problem in establishing such funds in the UK has been distribution. Most
unit trusts are sold through independent financial advisers, who receive a 3
per cent commission which is deducted from the initial charge.
Although Murray Johnstone is offering a renewal commission of 0.5 per cent
to advisers who keep their clients in the trusts for a year, the group may
find they will lack sufficient incentive to recommend its trusts. Murray may
have to rely on direct telephone sales or on fee-charging advisers.
In the last financial year unit trusts have been hard-pushed to compete with
investment trusts, their publicly quoted rivals, and this move may be a sign
of competitive pressures in the industry.
Mr Graeme Farquharson, investment director of Hill Martin, the financial
adviser group, said: 'It is an interesting move and I would not be surprised
if it doesn't prompt other unit trust managers to do it.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
