<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Canada to cut taxes and public spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OTTAWA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Canadian government yesterday proposed corporate and personal tax cuts
in a budget aimed at boosting public confidence ahead of the general
election expected to be called by mid-1993.
Saying that he was 'reducing spending in order to cut taxes', Mr Donald
Mazankowski, finance minister, also announced the abolition or streamlining
of 46 public-sector agencies and the complete withdrawal of Canadian combat
troops from Europe over the next three years.
Other measures include a cut from 10 per cent to 5 per cent in the
withholding tax on dividends paid to foreigners, and a radical overhaul of
the system of family allowances which have been part of the Canadian social
security net since 1945.
Mr Mazankowski projected a budget deficit of CDollars 27.5bn (Pounds 13.3bn)
in the year to March 31 1993, down from CDollars 31.4bn. The decline is
largely due to lower interest rates on debt servicing.
Next year's deficit will be well above earlier projections of a CDollars
24bn shortfall, and the government has pushed back its target of eliminating
borrowing requirements by one year, to 1995/96.
According to background documents published by the Finance Department,
Ottawa's deficit will be 4 per cent of GDP this year, compared with 6.8 per
cent in the US. Those positions were roughly reversed as recently as 1985.
The tax rate on manufacturing and processing will drop from 23 per cent to
22 per cent next January, and to 21 per cent in 1994. Capital cost
allowances for manufacturing and processing machinery go up immediately from
25 per cent to 30 per cent.
The surtax on personal taxes will fall from 5 per cent to 4 per cent of
basic tax on July 1 and to 3 per cent next January. In a nod to the
hard-pressed construction and real estate industry, Mr Mazankowski will
temporarily allow a portion of tax-sheltered retirement savings to be used
for buying or building a home.
The budget estimates are based on real GDP growth of 2.7 per cent this year
and 4.5 per cent in 1993. Inflation is expected to remain at 2.2 per cent
this year and next, while interest rates are forecast to continue dropping
for at least the next two years.
Mr Mazankowski expects the tax cuts to be entirely offset this year by
spending restraint, further privatisations and steps to improve tax
compliance. But the measures proposed yesterday will have a net stimulatory
impact of CDollars 730m in 1993/94.
Candidates for privatisation include the Royal Canadian Mint. Ottawa also
plans to abolish the Economic Council of Canada, which is one of the
country's leading economic think-tanks. Cabinet ministers are taking a 5 per
cent pay cut, and members of parliament and senior civil servants will no
longer be allowed to travel first-class.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
