FT  26 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Are you looking forward to another 10 hours of Inspector Morse? He returns
(8.00) for the first of five hefty murder stories. ITV's discovery that they
could hold a huge audience with two-hour slabs of this middlebrow,
inoffensive, beautifully filmed, rather repetitive, deeply English series
has changed attitudes towards scheduling. Time was when the broadcasters
strained to invent ways of keeping us interested by cunningly building one
appealing programme upon another. Now they simply say 'John - another ten
tons of Morse, please'.
Last week Anita Roddick, rarely off the box for months, was on that awful
interview-yourself series. Today she presents The Day The World Changed
(8.00 BBC2), choosing the day Britain's first department store opened.
Earlier, on The Gloria Hunniford Show Without Wogan (7.00 BBC1), the guests
include Mike McShane and Sandi Toksvig, who are in C4's 'Whose Line Is It
Anyway?' currently starring in a West End play, and about to open in a new
TV comedy.
Timewatch shows the first of a two-part programme on Tito (8.10 BBC2).
