<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Building societies fare badly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES fared badly on both sides of their business in January
according to figures published yesterday by the Building Societies
Association.
There was little sign of improvement in the societies' mortgage business.
Net new lending was Pounds 2.26bn, down from Pounds 2.53bn in December. Net
advances were up at Pounds 1.35bn from Pounds 1.16bn but this was well below
the Pounds 1.67bn for January last year, when figures were depressed by the
impending Gulf war.
In spite of the very poor showing in the mortgage market, Mr Mark Boleat,
director-general of the BSA, said seasonal factors were largely responsible.
'The recently reported signs of an upturn in housing market activity would
not have shown through in the January figures,' he said. City housing market
analysts described the figures as extremely disappointing, however.
Building societies enjoyed a modest upturn in their savings business in
January after two months in which there were net outflows of savings.
The improved performance in January, when Pounds 293m flowed into the
societies compared with an outflow of Pounds 54m in December, may have been
linked to the first anniversary of Tessa accounts.
The January figure was the highest since June. Mr Boleat said, however, the
underlying flow of savings was subdued and that this pattern seemed set to
continue for the foreseeable future.
</TEXT>
