ambition, making an illicit use of Hyundai group,' Mr Park Bum-jin, a DLP
spokesman, said.
Mr Chung initially refused to pay Won136.1bn (Pounds 101.8m) in penalty
taxes but later changed his mind. Since then, domestic banks have frozen
fresh loans to the group, the tax office has launched a second tax
investigation and the Securities Supervisory Board has postponed approval on
Hyundai units' rights issues for the sixth time, Hyundai officials said.
Daewoo, South Korea's fourth largest business group, said yesterday it was
suspending its plan for the first joint ventures with North Korea.
Disappointed by the outcome of talks between the prime ministers of North
and South last week, Seoul said any economic exchanges would be banned until
North Korea allowed inspection of nuclear facilities.
'We have also decided to put off the plan to send our executives to North
Korea for a feasibility study of the joint venture project,' a Daewoo
spokesman said.
