<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / World Trade News: Conference backs steps for Unctad reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARITA KENDALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARTAGENA, COLOMBIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Conference on Trade and Development (Unctad VIII) has approved an
institutional reform package designed to revitalise the organisation, Sarita
Kendall reports from Cartagena, Colombia.
The 171 member-nations have been working for change which, many delegates
hope, will influence other UN bodies.
Four new standing committees on commodities, poverty alleviation, economic
co-operation among developing countries and service sectors are to replace
most existing committees. Ad hoc working groups will deal with special
issues related to trade and development, such as investment, privatisation,
trade efficiency, exports and technology.
The declaration, 'The Spirit of Cartagena' agreed by members stressed: 'It
is important to overcome confrontation and foster a climate of genuine
co-operation and solidarity'. Unctad would give priority to problems facing
least developed countries and to the fight against poverty. The conference
showed strong agreement on economic growth policies: market economies, with
trade liberalisation and some privatisation, are almost universally accepted
by developing and industrialised nations.
</TEXT>
