<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / Banks 'face Soviet debt moratorium': Balance of payments
crisis threatens repayments by republics, Salomon Brothers warns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN commercial banks face the 'almost certain prospect' of a moratorium
on principal debt repayments by the former Soviet republics throughout this
year, according to a report by Salomon Brothers, the New York-based merchant
bankers.
This is because the republics are more preoccupied with their own domestic
problems and are suspicious of Russia's role in negotiating the debt.
Even if the political circumstances were more favourable, the report argues
that a moratorium would still be likely because the former Soviet republics
face a balance of payments crisis.
Under the terms of an inter-republican agreement signed last December,
western official creditors agreed to a temporary moratorium on medium and
long-term official debt.
This was followed by a temporary moratorium on payment of principal to
commercial banks. A moratorium on official credits was extended to the end
of 1992.
This agreement, which committed each republic towards contributing a share
of the convertible currency needed to make debt-service payments, was a
precondition for assent by official creditors to an extension of the
principal moratorium for all of this year.
Salomon Brothers say that the agreement is almost impossible to implement,
because:
'there is no way to ensure that each republic will contribute to the
debt-service pool, even if they had access to convertible currency income';
'all the republics, particularly the Ukraine, are suspicious of the (banking
and financial) apparatus that appears to be under the control of the Russian
republic.'
In recent weeks, the Ukraine government has repeatedly stated its opposition
to channeling debt service through a Russian-controlled institution.
'although the G7 (group of industrialised countries) warned the constituent
republics that their specific creditworthiness would be harmed if the debt
is not fully serviced, it is doubtful if the political elite in many
republics are overly concerned with international creditworthiness at a time
when popular discontent with food prices and shortages is the major
concern'.
Apart from political instability and inter-republican disagreements, the
report shows how balance-of-payments crises, caused by the rapid rise in
inflation, budget deficits, and an increase in the money supply, undermined
the worth of the rouble.
'The fundamental source of the Soviet Union's balance-of-payments crisis in
1991 was the rapid rise in both suppressed and open inflation during the
year, and the resulting disappearance of the rouble as a valid medium for
economic transactions,' says the report.
The public's lack of confidence in the rouble led to the internal flight to
hard currency by households - estimated to be between Dollars 5bn and
Dollars 10bn; the capital flight of hard currency abroad, estimated between
15bn and Dollars 40bn; and the hoarding abroad of hard currency by Soviet
enterprises in order to avoid the 40 per cent conversion tax on convertible
currency remissions.
The report argues that it is unlikely that the country's balance-of-payments
problems can be rectified in 1992.
</TEXT>
