<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 92 / S African Conservatives urged to reject reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH Africa's pro-apartheid Conservative party yesterday urged its
supporters to reject political reform, and vote 'no' in next month's
whites-only referendum.
Mr Andries Treurnicht, the Conservative leader, said the party's leadership
had wished to boycott the poll but rank and file members had outvoted them.
The party met for several hours on Monday night and all day yesterday to
resolve the dispute over participation.
Mr Treurnicht, announcing the start of the 'no' campaign in a radio
broadcast, referred several times to the possibility that the Conservatives
might lose the referendum, an outcome which would have grave political
consequences for the party.
'If we lose, this is not the end of the political war in South Africa,' he
said, adding, 'there is still a white nation that cannot be wished away.'
Asked whether his party expected to win the poll, Mr Treurnicht said only
that victory would be 'difficult, but it is possible'.
The Conservatives cannot count on a united right wing front in the
referendum campaign, which may also explain their reluctance to participate.
Yesterday Mr Eugene Terre Blanche, leader of the largest right wing splinter
group, the neo-Nazi Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging (AWB), or Afrikaner
Resistance Movement, said it would do all in its power to stop South
Africa's 3m whites voting in the poll.
'We cannot allow them to be led to the slaughter like lambs,' said the AWB
leader, who shares Conservative party demands for a return to apartheid and
creation of an all-white state, but supports the violence which the
Conservatives eschew.
He threatened violent resistance, saying blacks, who outnumber whites by
five to one, 'have declared war on your property rights . . . We are going
to have war.'
The referendum is a political gamble by Mr FW de Klerk, the president and
leader of the ruling National party, to marginalise the Conservatives.
He has challenged them to prove that they represent the majority of whites,
but has phrased the referendum question so that all but the most committed
racists will support it - including not only members of his party but also
supporters of the liberal Democratic party.
If they lose, the Conservatives will be left with little constitutional
outlet for their opposition, with only 42 seats in a parliament dominated by
102 National party MPs.
If Mr de Klerk loses the referendum, he will resign and call a general
election, which the Conservatives could expect to win on a pro-apartheid
ticket.
Stark choice for white voters, Page 4
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
