FT  25 FEB 92 / International Company News: Nordstrom turns in 11% fall in
profits to Dollars 40.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORDSTROM, the Seattle-based group once seen as a star in the US retail
sector but which has stalled recently, yesterday reported an 11.7 per cent
drop in fourth-quarter profits to Dollars 40.9m after tax.
This compared with Dollars 46.3m seen in the same three-month period, to
end-January, a year earlier, and was scored on sales up by 8.4 per cent at
Dollars 978m.
The final quarter's figures leave Nordstrom with a Dollars 135.8m net profit
for the year, against Dollars 115.8m in the previous 12 months. Earnings at
the pre-tax level were Dollars 217.2m for the year (Dollars 178.3m), and
Dollars 64.1m (Dollars 70.1m) for the quarter.
The fashion speciality retailer conceded that the retail environment had
been difficult, and that the fourth quarter had been weaker than originally
anticipated. It blamed this on December's performance in particular, and
maintained that sales in southern California were proving especially
'challenging'.
The company has 68 stores in nine states at present, biased towards the West
Coast. It expects to open another three 'full-line' stores this year - in
Minnesota, New Jersey and Maryland - and two clearance outlets.
</TEXT>
