<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Scottish constitutional stance may be reviewed by Tories
says Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR hinted yesterday that the government would review its
opposition to constitutional change for Scotland if the Conservatives won
the general election.
He said in a BBC radio interview recorded during his weekend visit to
Scotland: 'I have come to Scotland to set out the case for maintaining the
union in all its aspects . . . After the election we will take stock. For
the moment that's what I've done, that's all I have done and I'm going no
further.'
In a speech in Glasgow Mr Major urged Scots to reject independence and
devolution, and extolled the virtues of the union of the United Kingdom and
the role of Scotland within it. While only a minority of Scottish Tories
support constitutional change, many believe the party might have to change
its policy if it loses some of its nine Scottish seats in the general
election.
There was no sign of a change of policy from Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish
secretary, when he opened a five-hour debate on Scotland's constitutional
position at the Scottish Grand Committee of Scottish MPs in Edinburgh.
The debate, in the chamber built for the Scottish assembly planned by the
last Labour government, produced few new arguments. It was marked by
acrimony between Labour, which wants a devolved Scottish parliament, and the
Scottish National party, urging independence.
Mr Lang attacked the funding structure for Labour's planned parliament,
saying even if it were assigned all income tax and VAT raised in Scotland,
that was 'less than half of total identifiable public expenditure in
Scotland and less than a third of total government expenditure in Scotland'.
Even if the Scottish parliament, as Labour had said, imposed an extra 3p on
income tax in Scotland, it would only raise 2.5 per cent of government
revenue in Scotland.
In a whole range of ways, he said, 'a Scottish parliament would run amok
among the business and individual taxpayers of Scotland, to fund the
policies that would bring her to her knees'.
Mr Donald Dewar, the shadow Scottish secretary, defended Labour's proposals
for a Scottish parliament. Scots would be 'governed by representatives they
elect and will retain our links with the other countries which make up the
UK'.
Mr Lang, he said, 'always agonises over the impact of a Scottish parliament
on the UK. He never considers the damage being done to Scotland by the
present system'.
Mr Alex Salmond, leader of the SNP, said that a devolved Scottish parliament
would be unstable, as was the status quo. A devolved Scottish parliament
would depend for more than 90 per cent of its income on the discretion of
Westminster.
It would have little say in Scotland's dealing with the EC.
Parliament, Page 10
Joe Rogaly, Page 19
