<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / The Mood of Britain: It's a nightmare on Acacia Avenue but
boom time in Medomsley Road - Michael Cassell finds continued problems in
north-east England on the second stage of his pre-election trip around
Britain / Tyneside's Meadow Well estate gives the lie to any claims of
universal progress and well-being in modern Britain. It defies those who
profess to seek remedies for the most intractable social and economic
problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STREET names conjure up images of suburban, south-east gentility. But
Dorking, Didcot and Tonbridge Avenues represent the worst kind of
neighbourhood nightmare.
Barrack-style terraces of council homes, some boarded up and others
burned-out, line the roads at the heart of North Tyneside's Meadow Well
estate. Riots here in the autumn brought public uproar and unwelcome
notoriety.
'Nothing's changed round here. Nothing likely to,' muses Pat Moore, who
cruises the area in a battered flat-bed truck touting for scrap.
He laughs through tombstone-sized teeth at a torrent of abuse accusing him
of taking anything that is not bolted down. On Tyneside, even sets of
temporary traffic lights go missing, kidnapped for use in DIY discos.
Moore considers himself lucky not to live on the Meadow Well. He hails from
nearby Wallsend, where they launched the Mauretania, the ocean-going liner,
fitted out in a luxury unimaginable to its builders. Now, the town is famed
as the birthplace of Sting, the pop singer with an inspirational
rags-to-riches life story; these days he prefers London's leafy Highgate.
Many might suppose that the 'rags-to-riches' order has been reversed in
north-east England, once dubbed the cradle of 'carboniferous capitalism',
but more recently regarded as a state-dependent province populated by
Margaret Thatcher's 'moaning minnies'.
While it is not at all representative of a region struggling to break free
from its past, the Meadow Well - christened by some hopeful soul unburdened
by a sense of irony - reeks of despair and decay. It gives the lie to any
claims of universal progress and well-being in modern Britain. It defies
those who profess to seek remedies for the most intractable social and
economic problems.
Only the foolhardy would inquire here about the benefits recent years have
brought. On the Meadow Well nearly every home needs jobs and the only
benefits come in a book stamped Department of Social Security. The welfare
state is thriving here.
At the other end of Newcastle upon Tyne lies further deprivation. In the
city's West End, tyre tracks burned into the road trace the exploits of
daredevil delinquents. Nearly a quarter of children live with only one
parent and a similar proportion plays daily truant from school; half of
those aged under 24 are out of work.
With his wife the only breadwinner, Rakesh Chopra watches over the washing
and two noisy children in Westgate Hill Launderette off the Elswick Road. 'I
worked very hard but the factory moved away,' he says. 'They said I could
go, but there was not a home, so we have to stay.' Rakesh Chopra, it seems,
could not get on his bike.
Things look brighter just across the Tyne in Gateshead. JB Priestley
remarked that if anyone ever made money in Gateshead they had been careful
not to spend it there. Now, however, there is the MetroCentre, a vast
shopping shrine which has become a cliche for Geordie self-confidence,
luring bargain-hunters from as far afield as Oslo and Reykjavik.
But in spite of the deep and continuing antipathy in the region towards
Thatcher's values, the former prime minister made her mark. The north-east
was, reluctantly perhaps, gradually remoulded during her years in power.
Joe Mills, regional secretary of the TGWU general workers' union, recalls:
'She came up here and made it clear we'd get nowt for nowt. She said she
owed us nothing and if we wanted things to improve we'd have to damn well
fight for it.'
Mills, a board member of the Tyne and Wear Urban Development Corporation,
claims the fight was well under way before Thatcher's handbag swung into
town, but he acknowledges the region was stung into renewed action by her
attitude.
Mills' dual role neatly reflects the progress which has been made to unite
parties which traditionally stood on opposite sides of almost any argument.
Critics of the new partnership are angered by a perceived betrayal of old
allegiances. Promotional slogans such as 'the great north', aimed at the
rising number of inward investors, often elicit sneering cynicism. Most
people, however, welcome increasing co-operation between industry, councils
and regeneration agencies to replace the shipyards, coal mines and
heavy-engineering factories.
John Ward, regional director of Barclays Bank, says: 'There has been an
incredible change in attitudes in the last 10 years. The begging bowl
approach has gone. There is real partnership now, with business talking to
Labour-controlled councils displaying a refreshing pragmatism. Everyone is
pulling in the same direction and the enterprise culture has rubbed off.'
Professor Peter Taylor of Newcastle University reckons most people in
north-east England spent half the 1980s believing Thatcherism was inherently
evil and would just go away.
'Everyone waited for Labour to come back and put things right with
large-scale state solutions,' he says. 'But the agenda has changed and now
they are trying to get things done for themselves.'
John Tomaney, from the city's centre for urban and regional development
studies, sees a waning solidarity within the working class between those in
employment and those without jobs: 'They all used to stick together and help
each other out but now those in work are gradually distancing themselves
from the others.'
John Lee, a steelworker for 35 years whose skills were scrapped along with
the Consett works more than a decade ago, sees it happening all around him.
'My neighbour wasn't young when the plant shut and he has been out of a job
ever since. Many things have been pulled down, but they have not been
replaced by the training programmes and cash needed to rebuild jobs and
lives.'
He admits that, in the good old bad old days, unions and management spent
most of their energies fighting each other and needed their heads banging
together. But he still claims Consett did not need to close.
For some, new opportunities arose out of misfortune. Lee now works as a
probation officer in Consett, where the clinging red dust from the steel
works finally lifted to reveal a new generation of biotechnology companies,
plastics manufacturers and food processing specialists; for special steels
now read Phileas Fogg tortilla chips, produced by Derwent Valley Foods of
Medomsley Road.
The victims of some closures have tried to make it on their own, using
redundancy cash and enterprise allowance funds to run fish and chip shops or
sub-post offices. For some the gamble was regarded more as a last resort
than a confident, new beginning. Many would-be entrepreneurs quickly fail.
Not all, however. Six years ago, a redundant Robin Edgell set up a small
laundry service supplying companies around Durham. He has no regrets: 'I'm
not much better off and work twice as hard but I love being my own boss.'
Edgell says he used to vote Labour but now they are 'too quick to give with
one hand and take back with the other'. He adds: 'They talk as though
reasonable people won't mind paying a bit more tax. I'm sorry but I want to
pay less.'
Edgell would next like to try supplying the new industrial giants such as
Nissan at Washington. At the gates of the car manufacturing fortress,
workers decline to talk about employers with alien names and attitudes:
'Can't slag them off any more. They take it too personally.'
Further south, away from the land of the rising sun and the single-union
deal, lies Sacriston, a dismal, hilltop village where coalmining started in
1350 and ended in 1985. An old pit wheel stands in the town centre as a
reminder of things past.
Ian Tressler, a young storeman who wants to live in London, says Japanese
employers would be very welcome locally: 'We'll get karaoke down the pub and
make them feel at home. If they bring jobs with them, they'll never have to
buy their own pint.'
The rest of the articles in Michael Cassell's series will appear throughout
this week.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
