<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Main parties steady at 40% - Public
opinion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST WEEK'S public opinion polls have done little to change the overall
standing of the two main parties, which have been running roughly neck and
neck since the autumn.
In spite of the frenetic public relations skirmishing of recent weeks, both
the Conservatives and Labour remain locked together with just under 40 per
cent of the vote.
Neither party seems able to break this barrier and consolidate a position
where they can entertain realistic hopes of winning an overall majority of
seats.
Indeed, the FT's weighted average of the last nine opinion polls shows them
rocking back slightly from last week, as the Liberal Democrats apparently
continue to benefit from Mr Paddy Ashdown's admission that he had an affair
with his former secretary.
The Tories will now be setting more store than ever by the opportunity for
setting the agenda afforded by a tax-cutting Budget. Mr Neil Kinnock, the
Labour leader, must be hoping that the grim state of the economy sways more
support his way.
On their present performance, the FT's computer gives the Conservatives 312
seats (against 326 needed for an overall majority), Labour 296 and the
Liberal Democrats 18. In the current parliament, the Conservatives have 367
seats, Labour 230 and the Liberal Democrats 22.
