<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Commons renews terrorism measure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN incoming Labour government would seek an all-party consensus on new
anti-terrorist legislation, Mr Roy Hattersley, shadow home secretary, told
the Commons last night, Ivor Owen writes.
Before the Commons voted on renewal of the Prevention of Terrorism
(Temporary Provisions) Act Mr Kenneth Baker, dubbed 'the cheapest home
secretary of this century' by Mr Hattersley, confirmed that the Conservative
party would seek to make Labour's 'softness' on terrorism a central election
issue.
The home secretary suggested that Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, should
overrule Mr Hattersley on whose initiative the opposition had embarked on
the 'irresponsible' course of voting against extending the terrorism act.
Mr Baker emphasised that it was the last Labour government that introduced
the act, under which suspects can be detained for up to seven days for
questioning, or deported from mainland Britain.
Mr Hattersley said a Labour government would establish a judicial tribunal
to determine whether the period a suspect could be detained should be
extended from 48 hours to seven days.
Labour would also retain the provisions under which the IRA and other
terrorist groups could be proscribed, Mr Hattersley said.
Renewal of the act for a further period was approved by a government
majority of 185 (300-115).
Editorial Comment, Page 18
