<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Clark confirms he will step down -
Defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALAN CLARK, the colourful and controversial defence procurement minister,
yesterday announced that he will leave the Commons at the coming general
election.
His decision, after 18 years as a Tory MP, was revealed to his Plymouth
Sutton constituency association at the weekend. Mr Clark commented
yesterday: 'It was a difficult decision to make. And there were a whole
range of different considerations.'
When told that his agent had said he was leaving for personal reasons, Mr
Clark reacted with characteristic abruptness: 'I never said that. 'Personal
reasons' usually means there has been a scandal and I can assure you there
is nothing of that.'
At Westminster, most Conservative colleagues concluded that the wealthy
63-year-old minister has decided to retire to pursue his other interests,
including his work as a historian.
Political opponents claim, however, that his 4,013 majority over the Liberal
Democrats in Sutton has made the seat substantially less secure. At council
elections in May last year, there was criticism among local Tories of his
attention to the constituency and complaints that he had inadequately
defended the Devonport dockyard.
The Old Etonian son of Lord (Kenneth) Clark, the art historian, has long
proved one of the most outspoken, entertaining and quirky figures on the
Tory benches.
This year alone his aristocratic manner has been demonstrated in a court
appearance on speeding charges and contradicted by a magisterial attack on
bloodsports in the pages of The Guardian.
Since moving to his present post from the Department of Trade and Industry
in 1989, he has never been far from controversy. His cavalier manner has
sometimes outraged senior military commanders and his relations with Mr Tom
King, the defence secretary, are said to have been difficult.
His closeness to Mrs Margaret Thatcher strengthened his initial role at the
defence ministry, where his proposals for armed forces cuts set the tone for
the Options for Change review begun in 1990 - although the final reductions
were less drastic than Mr Clark's would have been.
In the midst of the military build-up in the Gulf, he again embarrassed
colleagues by challenging the usefulness of Nato and of keeping US forces in
Europe. On another occasion he accused European allies of 'running to the
cellars' while the US and Britain faced up to Iraq.
As MP for Plymouth Sutton, he appeared to pre-empt decisions on the future
of naval bases with reassurances on prospects for Plymouth's Devonport
facilities.
He was pursued by controversy over his role at the DTI in promoting British
exports to Iraq, although he denied 'giving a nod and wink' to exporters to
evade restrictions on arms sales.
A new Conservative candidate for the seat is expected to be selected within
three weeks.
Observer, Page 18
