<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Health union votes for Nalgo merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES IN the National Health Service's management style have prompted a
4,500-strong health workers' union to end more than 70 years of independence
and join the Nalgo public service union.
The Association of National Health Service Officers said the decision had
been made partly because of pressure from managers to break up national
bargaining in the NHS. This meant more union negotiators were needed.
Mr Roy Paterson, the association's general secretary, said another factor
was that changes in NHS management style had increased the number of members
facing disciplinary problems and needing union representation.
In addition, lay officials were finding it increasingly difficult to obtain
management permission for time off work.
Mr Paterson said the union had only three full-time staff, and members
needed the greater resources that joining Nalgo would provide.
The association's decision, approved by 79 per cent of voters in a
membership ballot, highlights the trend to a smaller number of larger
unions.
Many observers believe there will be four or five super-unions by the end of
the century and these will increasingly act as a home for smaller
organisations which would otherwise struggle to survive.
The association's vote comes after a year in which Nalgo has already
increased its membership by 15,000 to 760,000, against a trend of membership
decline in other unions. It provides a fillip for Nalgo leadership as it
prepares for a meeting of activists next week to discuss its plan to create
Britain's largest union - with 1.4m members  - by merging with the Nupe and
Cohse public service unions.
Mr Alan Jinkinson, Nalgo general secretary, said yesterday he was confident
a special conference of more than 1,500 union members next week would reject
attempts by some branches to stop the merger.
</TEXT>
