<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Clowes audit inquiry reopened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INVESTIGATION into the auditors of Barlow Clowes, the disgraced fund
management company which was closed by the Department of Trade and Industry
in 1988, has been reopened by the accountants' professional body.
The Joint Disciplinary Scheme (JDS) of the institutes of chartered
accountants in England, Wales and Scotland and the Association of Certified
Accountants confirmed yesterday that it had recommenced investigations into
the involvement of Spicer &amp; Pegler and Touche Ross as auditors to the
company.
The two firms, which merged in 1990, could be fined substantial sums and
ordered to pay inquiry costs - believed to total more than Pounds 1m already
 -if the inquiry finds against them.
The move comes after the 112-day Barlow Clowes trial ended earlier this
month. Mr Peter Clowes, the company's founder, was jailed for 10 years for
theft and fraud.
A committee established by the JDS to investigate the case began work in
January 1989 but was suspended in July last year following a request from
the Serious Fraud Office. The SFO is believed to have argued that continuing
the investigations before the trial could have interfered with the course of
justice.
The JDS inquiry was already well-advanced and it is believed that the costs
incurred to date make it the most expensive investigation yet undertaken. No
decision is expected from the committee before next year. The committee
comprises two accountants and a judge, with the assistance of an accountancy
firm.
The JDS examines questions against accountants and accountancy firms only
where allegations are complex and raise matters of substantial public
concern.
Last week it fined Arthur Young, now part of Ernst &amp; Young, Pounds 100,000
and Pounds 40,000 costs for its role as auditor to Milbury, the collapsed
house-building group controlled by Mr Jim Raper.
The only other case it is considering at present is against Arthur Young as
auditor to Alexander Howden and Minet, the insurance companies. Both
companies were criticised in a 1990 DTI report for the diversion of
reinsurance funds.
Most investigations are handled internally by the disciplinary committees of
the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales and the other
professional bodies.
Touche Ross said yesterday: 'We believe it is absolutely inappropriate for
us to comment on matters in this case at the moment.'
</TEXT>
