<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / Tax advisers urged to take tougher line with clients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAX ADVISERS should refuse to submit tax returns on behalf of clients who
cannot explain why information has been withheld, and should consider
ceasing to do any work for them, two professional bodies recommended
yesterday.
Advisers are also urged to highlight any items in a client's returns to the
Inland Revenue where they have doubts about the tax treatment.
The advice comes in guidelines published by the Institute of Taxation and
the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales. The guidance
comes after four years of discussion with the Revenue and are based on the
experiences of the institutes' members.
Mr Philip Hardman of Grant Thornton, one of the accountants involved in
drawing up the guidelines, said: 'If you are in any doubt about the tax
treatment you should give the Revenue full information and not mislead them.
The best advice is to give them full information and not to bury an item.'
The guidelines will become particularly appropriate next year when the
Revenue introduces a 'pay and file' corporate tax system similar to that
used in the US. There the onus is on companies to declare all tax for which
they believe they are liable.
The institutes have sought legal counsel suggesting that when this level of
disclosure takes place and the tax returns are approved by the Revenue, the
case cannot be re-opened at a later date. The Revenue argues that it retains
this right in certain instances.
The guidelines say there is no legal obligation to disclose information, but
advisers should use their professional judgment where there is doubt. They
add that normal client confidentiality may be overruled where there is a
public duty to disclose information.
Ethical Rules and Practice Guidelines. ICAEW, Gloucester House, 399 Silbury
Blvd, Milton Keynes MK9 2HL. Free.
SIX Labour MPs headed by Mr Austin Mitchell, member for Great Grimsby, are
demanding independent regulation of the auditing industry, David Owen
writes. They cite the sector's lack of confidence 'in the light of the
rising tide of financial scandals'.
Their early-day motion deplores 'the fact that where auditors should act to
protect and warn the public and shareholders, too many have been drawn into
a collusive relationship with directors by their desire to sell non-auditing
services to firms'.
</TEXT>
