<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gold closed below Dollars 350 a troy ounce on the London bullion market in
lethargic trading dominated by technical factors. The morning fix of Dollars
349 marked a five-month low, but the market recovered a little ground on
bargain hunting and short covering. The April contract on Comex had
recovered by midday from a lifetime low of Dollars 350.20 struck shortly
after the opening. On the LME aluminium rose on the back of the copper
market, but three-month metal met resistance around Dollars 1,340 a tonne.
Dealers are expecting another increase in stocks today. London robusta
coffee prices closed down sharply while New York arabicas well down at
midday after the ICO indicator hit a 17-year low of 54.57 cents a lb. New
York traders said there was little fresh fundamental influence in the market
and prices remained weighed by abundant supply and an absence of strong
demand. May scored a low of 67.20 cents a lb. 'The picture is bleak. There's
a burdensome supply for the near-term and we've got a lot of new crop,' said
one analyst. Robustas have fallen by about Dollars 100 a tonne since
mid-January. 'With the state of the market at the moment we can see it
declining further,' a London dealer said.
Compiled from Reuters
