FT  25 FEB 92 / International Company News: First-half drop for Murdoch's NZ
unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ADVERTISING revenue of the New Zealand, Australia and US publications of
Wellington-based Independent Newspapers (INL) was hit by recession, leading
to a 9.7 per cent fall in first-half net profits to NZDollars 16.4m
(USDollars 8.9m).
Mr Alan Burnet, chairman, said the result was satisfactory considering the
depressed economic conditions in the countries where the group owns
newspapers. INL is 51 per cent owned by News Corporation, the media group
controlled by Mr Rupert Murdoch.
Advertising revenues fell 7.1 per cent in New Zealand and 10.7 per cent in
Australia compared with the same period of 1990.
Mr Burnet said the group experienced some recovery, especially in its South
Island New Zealand newspapers. Interest costs would fall for the year after
NZDollars 14.24m of debt was repaid.
The closure of the loss-making Auckland Star during the period, plus static
newspaper prices was expected to mean that the full-year result would show
considerable improvement. Satisfactory results were achieved by Gordon and
Gotch, the subsidiary which is the largest newspaper and magazine
distributor in Australasia.
Circulation of the paid newspapers had been stable, with the Christchurch
Press and the Waikato Times showing significant gains. Sales rose 14.9 per
cent to NZDollars 471.39m from NZDollars 410.3m.
Pre-tax profits fell 8.6 per cent to NZDollars 26.11m. Tax took NZDollars
9.83m against NZDollars 10.37m. A maintained 7 cents a share dividend was
declared.
