FT  25 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Principal Hotels goes into administration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRINCIPAL Hotels Group, the shares of which were suspended last Friday while
the company's financial position was clarified, went into administrative
receivership last night with borrowings of more than Pounds 100m.
The Harrogate-based group has 19 hotels in Britain, two each Denmark and the
Netherlands and one in France. Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte, the accountants,
will carry on running the group to try and sell it. About 1,000 jobs are
involved.
Mr Edward Klempka, a partner in Coopers' Leeds office, said: 'The hotels are
viable. We will continue to expand until they can be sold.' A management
buy-out, trade sale or even reflotation are possible options.
Hotels include the Norbreck Castle in Blackpool, the Palace in Copenhagen
and the Douglas in Aberdeen. The group was formed in 1988 as a hotels and
financial services operation, but sold the latter in 1989. It borrowed
heavily to refurbish old hotels on prominent sites and became over-geared.
The recession hit bookings and the vital conference trade, pushing losses
for the 16 months to last October to more than Pounds 10m. In January,
Principal postponed interest payments on its 11 per cent convertible
unsecured loan stock pending restructuring.
